PSI CA PART I

Introduction

1.1 Research Question

A persons self esteem can be impacted by a range of social, pyschological and physical factors. This analysis is concerned with a persons sense of being in control and whether a persons gender and age group may also influence a persons self esteem as measured using a self esteem questionnaire. Can a persons perceived sense of control, as measured using the Perceived Control of Internal States Scale (PCOISS) scale, be considered to influence a persons self-esteem, as measured using a self esteem questionnaire, and do differences exist in a persons self esteem based on their gender and age group?

1.1 Hypotheses

The particular hypotheses to be investigated are:

Hypothesis 1:

H0: There is no correlation between cigarettes smoked per day and Rate of impact of sleep on energy level

HA: There is a correlation between cigarettes smoked per day and Rate of impact of sleep on energy level

Hypothesis 2:

H0:There is no difference in sleep impact on mood for the restless sleeper or not a restless sleeper

HA:There is a difference in sleep impact on mood for the restless sleeper or not a restless sleeper

Hypothesis 3:

H0:There is no correlation between level of anxiety and sleep impact on overall well-being

HA:There is a correlation between level of anxiety and sleep impact on overall well-being

Hypothesis 4:

H0:There is no difference in drinks containing caffeine per day or general health rate

HA:There is a difference in drinks containing caffeine per day or general health rate

Hypothesis 5:

H0:There is no difference in level of depression or satisfaction with the amount of sleep

HA:There is a difference in level of depression or satisfaction with the amount of sleep

Report of normality analysis

Cigarettes smoked per day is represented by a scale variable in the dataset which was calculated from the Overall Health questionnaire. Inspection of the histogram and normality plot (see figure 1 and figure 2) shows that the distribution does not conform exactly to a normal distribution. Inspection of standardized normal scores for skewness and kurtosis indicated that while both do not fall with an acceptable range of +/-2, (skewness of 2.8834724 SE=0.4140393, kurtosis of 11.6571074 SE=0.8280787. Further inspection of the variable using standardized scores showed that 0.37% standardised scores were inside the acceptable range of +/3.29. Total self esteem will therefore be treated as a not normal within this analysis (stat.desc(sleep$smokenum, basic=F))

Report of normality analysis

Rate of impact of sleep on mood is represented by a scale variable in the dataset which was calculated from the Total Perceived Control questionnaire. Inspection of the histogram and normality plot (see figure 5 and figure 6) shows that the distribution does not conform exactly to a normal distribution. Inspection of standardized normal scores for skewness and kurtosis indicated that while skewness was not an issue falling with an acceptable range of +/-2, (skewness of -0.2531217 SE=0.2208631), kurtosis was outside acceptable bounds, (kurtosis of -0.831127 SE=0.4417261 . Further inspection of the variable using standardized scores showed that only 0 or 0% standardised scores were outside the acceptable range of +/3.29. Total perceived control of internal states will therefore be treated as a normal within this analysis pastecs::stat.desc(sleep$impact1, basic=F)

##1.1 Hypotheses

The particular hypotheses to be investigated are:

Hypothesis 1:

H0: There is no correlation between cigarettes smoked per day and Rate of impact of sleep on energy level

HA: There is a correlation between cigarettes smoked per day and Rate of impact of sleep on energy level

cor.test(sleep$smokenum, sleep$impact2, method = "spearman")
## Warning in cor.test.default(sleep$smokenum, sleep$impact2, method =
## "spearman"): Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  sleep$smokenum and sleep$impact2
## S = 1108.7, p-value = 0.5681
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##        rho 
## -0.1442013
#spearman correlation
cor.test(sleep$smokenum, sleep$impact2, method = "kendall")
## Warning in cor.test.default(sleep$smokenum, sleep$impact2, method =
## "kendall"): Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Kendall's rank correlation tau
## 
## data:  sleep$smokenum and sleep$impact2
## z = -0.46189, p-value = 0.6442
## alternative hypothesis: true tau is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##         tau 
## -0.08392429
#kendall correlation to calculate accute p-value
scatter<-ggplot(sleep, aes(sleep$smokenum, sleep$impact2))
scatter + geom_point()+ geom_smooth(method = 'lm', colour='Red', se=F)+ labs(x="cigarettes smoked per day", y="rate of impact of sleep on energy level ")
## Warning: Removed 253 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 253 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The relationship between cigarettes smoked per day and rate impact of sleep on energy level was investigated using a Spearman correlation because ther was no normality so used a non-parametric Test . A small/weak and negative correlation was found ( rho =-0.1442013 S = 1108.7, p-value = 0.6442). There is evidence to support accepting the null hypothesis that there is relationship between cigarettes smoked per day and rate impact of sleep on energy level

Hypothesis 2:

H0:There is no difference in sleep impact on mood for the restless sleeper or not a restless sleeper

HA:There is a difference in sleep impact on mood for the restless sleeper or not a restless sleeper

Independent t-test

diff1<- describeBy(sleep$impact1, group = sleep$restlss)
diff1
## 
##  Descriptive statistics by group 
## group: 1
##    vars  n mean   sd median trimmed  mad min max range  skew kurtosis   se
## X1    1 60 6.07 2.19    6.5    6.19 2.22   1  10     9 -0.56    -0.08 0.28
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## group: 2
##    vars  n mean   sd median trimmed  mad min max range skew kurtosis   se
## X1    1 60  5.4 2.64    5.5    5.35 3.71   1  10     9 0.03    -1.34 0.34
sleep$restlss <- as.character(as.numeric(sleep$restlss))
#Conduct Levene's test for homogeneity of variance in library car
car::leveneTest(impact1 ~ restlss, data = sleep)
## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value   Pr(>F)   
## group   1  7.4684 0.007246 **
##       118                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#Conduct the t-test from package stats
t.test(impact1 ~ restlss, var.equal=TRUE, data = sleep)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  impact1 by restlss
## t = 1.5077, df = 118, p-value = 0.1343
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2089583  1.5422917
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 1 mean in group 2 
##        6.066667        5.400000

A Levenes test for homogeneity of variance was conducted and indicated equality of variance for sleep impact on mood for restless sleeper(group1) or not restless sleeper(group2) respondents (F=7.468, Pr=0.007). An independent-samples t-test was conducted to compare sleep impact on mood for group1 and group2 respondents. No significant difference in the scores for was found (M=33.17, SD= 5.71 for female respondents, M= 34.02, SD= 4.91 for male respondents), (t= 1.5077, p = 0.1343). The eta square statistic also indicated a very small effect size (0.006). While the result is statistical significance which indicates there is evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no difference in self esteem scores for respondents of different gender, the very small effect size is a concern and therefore the result should be treated with caution.

Hypothesis 3:

H0:There is no correlation between level of anxiety and sleep impact on overall well-being

HA:There is a correlation between level of anxiety and sleep impact on overall well-being

cor.test(sleep\(anxiety, sleep\)impact6, method = spearman) scatter<-ggplot(sleep, aes(sleep\(anxiety, sleep\)impact6)) scatter + geom_point()+ geom_smooth(method = lm, colour=Red, se=F)+ labs(x=anxiety, y=sleep impact on overall well-being)

Hypothesis 4:

H0:There is no difference in drinks containing caffeine per day or general health rate

HA:There is a difference in drinks containing caffeine per day or general health rate

describeBy(sleep\(caffeine, sleep\)healthrate)

kruskal.test(caffeine ~ healthrate, data=sleep) tmp<- dunnTest(x=sleep\(caffeine, g=factor(sleep\)healthrate), method=bonferroni)

print(tmp, dunn.test.results = TRUE)

Hypothesis 5:

H0:There is no difference in level of depression or satisfaction with the amount of sleep

HA:There is a difference in level of depression or satisfaction with the amount of sleep

describeBy(sleep\(depress, sleep\)satsleep)

kruskal.test(depress ~ satsleep, data=sleep) tmp<- dunnTest(x=sleep\(depress, g=factor(sleep\)satsleep), method=bonferroni)

print(tmp, dunn.test.results = TRUE)
